<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911028-0134</DOCNO><DOCID>911028-0134.</DOCID><HL>   South African Air Ban Lifted</HL><DATE>10/28/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><MS>CONSUMER CYCLICAL (CYC)</MS><IN>AIRLINES (AIR)</IN><NS>TRAVEL (TVL)</NS><GV>TRANSPORTATION DEPARTMENT (TRN)</GV><RE>AFRICA (AF)NORTH AMERICA (NME)NEW YORK (NY)SOUTH AFRICA (SF)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa -- After a five-year ban, SouthAfrican Airways said it received permission to resume flightsto the U.S.   The airline said that having been cleared by the U.S.Department of Transportation, it will begin flying to NewYork twice a week starting Sunday.</LP><TEXT>   The carrier was banned from U.S. airports in November1986, after Washington imposed sanctions against South Africato protest apartheid. President Bush lifted most sanctions inJune to reward President F.W. de Klerk's political reforms.</TEXT></DOC>